{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531383"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:13:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:13:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14594"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14594"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.53,0.07,0.02,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7287"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57207"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7287"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14594"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42666"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"131"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1287"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17797"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57207"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit following a subarachnoid haemorrhage. She presented to the Emergency Department with sudden onset severe headache six hours ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears drowsy with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 13 (E3 V4 M6). Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 175/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her pupils are equal and reactive to light. CT brain shows blood in the basal cisterns, and CT angiogram reveals a middle cerebral artery aneurysm. She is awaiting neurosurgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management priority?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start intravenous dexamethasone","Commence intravenous labetalol","Commence phenytoin prophylaxis","Begin therapeutic hypothermia","Administer mannitol"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an aneurysmal subarachnoid haemorrhage (SAH) and has significant hypertension that requires urgent management. The most immediate priority is to prevent rebleeding, which carries a high mortality rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing intravenous labetalol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate immediate priority. Labetalol is the first-line agent for blood pressure control in SAH, with a target systolic blood pressure below 160 mmHg to reduce the risk of early rebleeding before definitive aneurysm treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended in SAH management. Multiple clinical trials have shown no benefit from corticosteroids in improving outcomes after SAH, and they may increase complications including infection risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhenytoin prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely recommended in SAH unless seizures occur. The evidence for prophylactic antiepileptic medications in preventing seizures after SAH is limited.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETherapeutic hypothermia\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard treatment for SAH. While it has been studied in various neurological conditions, there is insufficient evidence to support its routine use in SAH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMannitol\u003C/strong\u003E would only be indicated if there were signs of raised intracranial pressure, which are not present in this case. The patient\u0027s GCS of 13 and normal pupillary responses do not suggest significant mass effect requiring osmotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important aspects of SAH management include maintaining euvolaemia, monitoring for hydrocephalus, and arranging urgent aneurysm securing (either by surgical clipping or endovascular coiling). Regular neurological observations are essential to detect any deterioration that might indicate complications such as rebleeding or delayed cerebral ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early recognition and treatment of delayed cerebral ischaemia is critical in subarachnoid haemorrhage management.","Intravenous labetalol is a first-line therapy for acute hypertension in subarachnoid haemorrhage.","Routine corticosteroids are not recommended in subarachnoid haemorrhage management."],"references":["Highton D, Smith M. Intensive care management of subarachnoid haemorrhage. Journal of Intensive Care Society, 2013 (ed 14 vol 1). Available: https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/pdf/10.1177/175114371301400108","Ziu E, Khan Suheb MZ, Mesfin FB. Subarachnoid Hemorrhage. [Updated 2023 Jun 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441958/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42666"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14594"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42666"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T12:05:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T12:08:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"ite